INSERT INTO items VALUES(80,1659,314,'ECON_DEV_REDEV','ORD 16-039','ECON_DEV_REDEV ZONE_USE_PERMIT AFF_HOUS_REDEV The first choice, ECON_DEV_REDEV, was made because the agenda item is about authorizing the execution of a redevelopment agreement, which directly aligns with economic development activities aimed at revitalizing specific areas. The mention of the Oak Park Economic Development Corporation further reinforces this classification as an initiative focused on economic revitalization.','U. ORD 16-039 An Ordinance Authorizing the Execution of a Redevelopment Agreement (708 Lake Street) by the Village of Oak Park as Recommended by the Oak Park Economic Development Corporation (Oak Park EDC)','93a8d9aa-36a8-4357-a046-469c1c135e93',7,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('U. ORD 16-039 An Ordinance Authorizing the Execution of a Redevelopment Agreement\n(708 Lake Street) by the Village of Oak Park as Recommended by the Oak\nPark Economic Development Corporation (Oak Park EDC)\nVillage Manager Pavlicek stated that this is for a Redevelopment Agreement for District\nHouse, a mixed use development at the former Tasty Dog location.\nDirector of Development Customer Services Tammie Grossman stated that the developer,\nRanquist Development Group, will pay the Village $1.8 million, which is inclusive of\n$280,000 towards the Village''s Affordable Housing Fund. In addition, the developer will\nassume any environmental expenses that the Village may be subject to. A future Study\nSession will be planned to discuss the Affordable Housing Fund\nChris Dillion, a representative for Ranquist, thanked the Board and staff for their work and\nlooks forward to beginning the project.\nVillage Trustee Button Ott asked that the Affordable Housing Fund meeting be scheduled\nsoon.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Barber, seconded by Village Trustee Lueck, that\nthis Ordinance be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the vote\nwas as follows:\nAYES: 6 - Village Trustee Barber, Village Trustee Button Ott, Village Trustee Lueck, Village\nTrustee Salzman, Village Trustee Tucker, and Village President Abu-Taleb\nNAYS: 0\nABSENT: 1 - Village Trustee Brewer\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(81,1973,121,'ZONE_USE_COMM','MOT 16-057','``` ZONE_USE_COMM AFF_HOUS_DEV ZONE_USE_PERMIT ``` The first choice, "ZONE_USE_COMM," was made because the agenda item involves referring a planned development application for a mixed-use development to the Plan Commission. This includes commercial uses on the first floor, which aligns with the category concerning commercial zoning issues and special use permits for businesses and developments. The description specifies commercial zoning issues, making it the most appropriate fit given the details of the agenda item.','V. MOT 16-057 A Motion to Refer to the Plan Commission a Planned Development Application for the Property Located at 702-708 Lake Street and 139-147 North Euclid Avenue for a Five Story Mixed Use Development Consisting of Commercial Uses on the First Floor','ae4e4ca6-bb4e-4040-abf8-65bf0f057865',7,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-10-28T01:59:44',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(82,2094,737,'ZONE_USE_PERMIT','ORD 16-028','ZONE_USE_PERMIT ZONE_USE_COMM AFF_HOUS_DEV The first choice, "ZONE_USE_PERMIT," is made because the agenda item specifically mentions adopting an ordinance granting a Special Use Permit for a major planned development. This directly aligns with the classification of "ZONE_USE_PERMIT," which covers special use permits for businesses and housing developments within the municipality. The details in the agenda item, including the mixed-use nature of the development (residential, commercial, and parking uses), support this classification.','W. ORD 16-028 Concur with the Plan Commission''s Recommendations and Adopt an Ordinance Granting a Special Use Permit for a Major Planned Development for a Mixed Use Multiple Story Development with Residential, Commercial and Parking Uses at the Property Lo','b9b109e1-2c66-427f-9dce-969de261a977',7,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('W. ORD 16-028 Concur with the Plan Commission’s Recommendations and Adopt an\nOrdinance Granting a Special Use Permit for a Major Planned Development\nfor a Mixed Use Multiple Story Development with Residential, Commercial\nand Parking Uses at the Property Located at 325-331 Harlem Avenue and\n100-107 South Maple Avenue\nVillage Manager Pavlicek stated that this Item and the next two are related to the Lincoln\nDevelopment at South Boulevard and Harlem.\nPlan Commission Chair David Mann noted that the commission initially had some\nconcerns in terms of the design of the development. They worked with the developer to\nmodify certain aspects of the design. However, the commission noted that this is going\nto be one of three very large developments downtown. Traditionally, they ask for a post\noccupancy traffic study to be completed after each project, but instead are\nrecommending that one larger traffic study be done with the impacts of all three.\nA representative for the developer thanked staff and others for working with them.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Tucker, seconded by Village Trustee Button Ott,\nthat this Ordinance be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the\nvote was as follows:\nAYES: 6 - Village Trustee Barber, Village Trustee Button Ott, Village Trustee Lueck, Village\nTrustee Salzman, Village Trustee Tucker, and Village President Abu-Taleb\nNAYS: 0\nABSENT: 1 - Village Trustee Brewer\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(83,2831,104,'ZONE_USE_AMEND','ORD 16-029','ZONE_USE_AMEND ZONE_USE_RES ZONE_USE_PERMIT The first choice, ZONE_USE_AMEND, was made because the agenda item involves an ordinance authorizing a vacation of portions of a street, which is typically associated with zoning and land use amendments. This ordinance likely requires changing or updating the existing zoning regulations or plans for the area in question, which fits the description of ZONE_USE_AMEND as it deals with amendments to zoning ordinances and land use regulations.','X. ORD 16-029 An Ordinance Authorizing the Vacation of Certain Portions of South Maple Avenue within the OP Boulevard, LLC (Lincoln Property Company) Planned Development Site located at 325-331 Harlem Avenue and 100-107 South Maple Avenue in the Village Of','ca393898-4eae-4d70-8961-75c31bbe7acb',7,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-10-28T01:59:44',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(84,2935,221,'ECON_DEV_REDEV','ORD 16-049','ECON_DEV_REDEV ZONE_USE_AMEND PROC_ORD_RULES The agenda item, "An Ordinance Authorizing the Execution of a Second Amendment to Redevelopment Agreement - South Boulevard and Harlem Site," most closely fits the classification ECON_DEV_REDEV. This is because the nature of the item involves an amendment to a redevelopment agreement, implying efforts to revitalize or further develop a specific area (South Boulevard and Harlem Site). The term "redevelopment" is explicitly mentioned, aligning directly with the ECON_DEV_REDEV focus on redevelopment projects aimed at supporting business expansion and revitalizing commercial areas.','Y. ORD 16-049 An Ordinance Authorizing the Execution of a Second Amendment to Redevelopment Agreement - South Boulevard and Harlem Site by the Village of Oak Park, a home rule unit of government','f8cdda2c-fd6e-4772-bd62-f094d20e734d',7,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('Y. ORD 16-049 An Ordinance Authorizing the Execution of a Second Amendment to\nRedevelopment Agreement - South Boulevard and Harlem Site by the\nVillage of Oak Park, a home rule unit of government\nVillage Manager Pavlicek stated that the original Redevelopment Agreement did not\nspecify rates in the public parking portion of what will be a privately owned garage. Staff\nhas worked with the developer to identify a range or a cap on those rates. Village\nPresident Abu-Taleb thanked the developers for working with the Village in terms of\nagreeing to put a cap on the rate to make it comparable to the other garages downtown.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Barber, seconded by Village Trustee Tucker,\nthat this Ordinance be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the\nvote was as follows:\nAYES: 6 - Village Trustee Barber, Village Trustee Button Ott, Village Trustee Lueck, Village\nTrustee Salzman, Village Trustee Tucker, and Village President Abu-Taleb\nNAYS: 0\nABSENT: 1 - Village Trustee Brewer\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(85,3156,286,'ECON_DEV_REDEV','ORD 16-056','ECON_DEV_REDEV ZONE_USE_AMEND AFF_HOUS_REDEV The primary reason for choosing ECON_DEV_REDEV as the best fit is because the agenda item involves an ordinance related to a redevelopment agreement. The description "Authorizing the Execution of the First Amendment to the Amended and Restated Redevelopment Agreement" indicates that the focus is on a redevelopment project, which aligns closely with the category of ECON_DEV_REDEV. This category specifically addresses redevelopment projects aimed at revitalizing areas and supporting expansion, which appears to fit the nature of the agenda item provided.','Z. ORD 16-056 An Ordinance Authorizing the Execution of the First Amendment to the Amended and Restated Redevelopment  Agreement - Lake Street / Westgate / North Boulevard Site','72d87c16-2824-4104-b9d8-992d49fe561d',7,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('Z. ORD 16-056 An Ordinance Authorizing the Execution of the First Amendment to the\nAmended and Restated Redevelopment Agreement - Lake Street /\nWestgate / North Boulevard Site\nVillage Manager Pavlicek stated that the developer had the option to add additional retail\nspace to the southwest corner of the parking garage as part of the Amended and\nRestated Development Agreement. The developer has secured a retail tenant and this\namendment is necessary to authorize that option and reduce the parking count\naccordingly.\nAndy Stein with Clark Street Development spoke about marketing efforts and recruitment\nfor the development. He also clarified that there will only be a loss of four parking spots.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Barber, seconded by Village Trustee Button Ott,\nthat this Ordinance be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the\nvote was as follows:\nAYES: 6 - Village Trustee Barber, Village Trustee Button Ott, Village Trustee Lueck, Village\nTrustee Salzman, Village Trustee Tucker, and Village President Abu-Taleb\nNAYS: 0\nABSENT: 1 - Village Trustee Brewer\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(86,3442,344,'ECON_DEV_INC','RES 16-222','ECON_DEV_INC ECON_DEV_COMM ECON_DEV_REDEV The first choice, "ECON_DEV_INC," was made because the agenda item describes a resolution approving a memorandum of understanding related to the preliminary formation of "i-ECO," which suggests an initiative aimed at economic development. The term "i-ECO" could imply a focus on innovation and economic collaboration, which aligns with incentives for business development and financial support for growth indicated by the "ECON_DEV_INC" classification. The phrase "authorizing its execution" also implies a concrete step towards realizing economic development goals, further supporting this classification choice.','T. RES 16-222 A Resolution Approving a Memorandum of Understanding Related to the Preliminary Formation of i-ECO and Authorizing its Execution','4b452753-e9ba-452b-b937-bc37b53f23be',7,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-10-28T01:59:44',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(87,3786,552,'TRANS_INF_TRANS','RES 16-093','TRANS_INF_TRANS PUB_ENG_HEAR ENV_SUS_CLIM The reason I chose "TRANS_INF_TRANS" as the first classification is because the agenda item pertains to the installation of bike share stations, which directly relates to transportation infrastructure initiatives involving public transit and alternative transportation methods. "TRANS_INF_TRANS" encompasses projects that involve transportation and public transit improvements, and a bike share program is a key component of a city''s public transit and transportation strategy, promoting sustainability and accessibility.','AA. RES 16-093 A Resolution Approving the Locations for Installation of Thirteen Bike Share Stations','4508fc59-9cda-440f-9eb8-37c6a8860257',7,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('AA. RES 16-093 A Resolution Approving the Locations for Installation of Thirteen Bike\nShare Stations\nVillage Manager Pavlicek stated that the Village Board had authorized agreements with\nthe City of Chicago to join the Divvy bike sharing program. Through the planning process,\n12 stations were originally recommended and a 13th was added to ensure Northeast Oak\nPark was covered in the first phase. The Board had asked staff to bring back the final\nsite selections, which is included in the Board Packets and online for public viewing.\nDirector of Parking and Mobility Services Jill Velan noted that the federal grant provided\ncovers the cost of 12 stations and answered questions from the Board.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Tucker, seconded by Village Trustee Salzman,\nthat this Resolution be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the\nvote was as follows:\nAYES: 6 - Village Trustee Barber, Village Trustee Button Ott, Village Trustee Lueck, Village\nTrustee Salzman, Village Trustee Tucker, and Village President Abu-Taleb\nNAYS: 0\nABSENT: 1 - Village Trustee Brewer\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(88,4338,64,'PUB_WRK_ROADS','RES 16-217','PUB_WRK_ROADS PUB_WRK_UTIL PUB_WRK_LIGHT The first choice, PUB_WRK_ROADS, was made because the agenda item concerns a resolution involving a change order to a contract for a project that includes sidewalk and curb & gutter replacement. These types of projects are typically related to road and street maintenance, falling under the category of public works dealing with roads. The emphasis on sidewalk and curb likely means it falls under maintenance and infrastructure enhancement typically covered by this category.','AB. RES 16-217 A Resolution Authorizing a Change Order to the Contract with J. Nardulli Concrete, Inc., for Project 15-3, 2015 Sidewalk and Curb & Gutter Replacement, for an Additional $25,000.00','cdd58036-5d3d-4a38-8c05-c78c4bf8a27e',7,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-10-28T01:59:44',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(89,4402,358,'PROC','ORD 16-059','PROC_ORD_RULES ZONE_USE_AMEND PROC_VILLAGE_POLICY The first choice, PROC_ORD_RULES, was made because the agenda item pertains to an ordinance amendment, specifically regarding amendments to existing municipal law concerning alcoholic liquor dealers. This classification directly aligns with the task of amending procedural or ordinance rules within the municipality, as the agenda item involves changes to specific sections of existing ordinances.','AC. ORD 16-059 An Ordinance Amending Chapter 3 ("Alcoholic Liquor Dealers"), Article 8 ("List of Licenses for Each License Class"), Section 3-8-1 ("Number of Licenses to be Issued Per License Class") and Section 3-8-2 ("Licenses by Name and Address Per Lic','59efbada-c345-4f85-a275-cace8c50e93f',7,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('AC. ORD 16-059 An Ordinance Amending Chapter 3 (“Alcoholic Liquor Dealers”), Article 8\n(“List of Licenses for Each License Class”), Section 3-8-1 (“Number of\nLicenses to be Issued Per License Class”) and Section 3-8-2 (“Licenses by\nName and Address Per License”) of the Oak Park Village Code for the\nIssuance of a Club Class D-3 Liquor License to Oak Park Fitness, LLC\nVillage Attorney Paul Stephanides stated that this will allow for beer and wine at Oak\nPark Fitness, LLC at 1114 Lake Street.\nGale Landers, owner of Fitness Formula Clubs, stated that there have been requests for\nbeen and wine from a lot of the members, and that the company sees it as a social\nopportunity. He noted that that this type of license exists at several of their other clubs so\nthey have experience with liquor service. Mr. Landers answered questuions from the\nBoard.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Button Ott, seconded by Village Trustee Tucker,\nthat this Ordinance be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the\nvote was as follows:\nAYES: 5 - Village Trustee Barber, Village Trustee Button Ott, Village Trustee Lueck, Village\nTru