INSERT INTO items VALUES(357,2326,756,'PROC','ORD 17-201','PROC_ORD_RULES PROC_VILLAGE_RULES ZONE_USE_AMEND The agenda item "An Ordinance Amending Chapter 30 ("Special Events"), Article 1 ("General Regulations") of the Oak Park Village Code" involves making amendments to existing ordinances. This fits best under the symbolism name PROC_ORD_RULES, which includes discussions and actions around the adoption, modification, and repeal of municipal laws. The description aligns with the nature of the agenda item, as it deals with amending village code regulations.','S. ORD 17-201 An Ordinance Amending Chapter 30 ("Special Events"), Article 1 ("General Regulations") of the Oak Park Village Code','32c484da-0ff0-4edd-b44e-4603b2e01cec',33,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-10-28T01:59:44',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(358,3082,291,'ECON_DEV_REDEV','ORD 17-187','ECON_DEV_REDEV ZONE_USE_AMEND AFF_HOUS_REDEV The first choice, ECON_DEV_REDEV, was made because the agenda item specifically refers to a "First Amendment to the Redevelopment Agreement," which suggests that this is about modifying or expanding a pre-existing redevelopment project. The agenda item involves the Village and District House LLC, which typically align with the activities of commercial or mixed-use redevelopment projects aimed at revitalizing certain areas. Moreover, these projects often seek to enhance economic growth, fitting well with the category of economic development through redevelopment.','AC. ORD 17-187 An Ordinance Appproving a First Amendment to the Redevelopment Agreement  between the Village of Oak Park and District House LLC (708 Lake Street) and Authorizing its Execution','1047238d-3e85-42bc-9823-251fcced47c4',33,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-10-28T01:59:44',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(359,3373,629,'ECON_DEV_REDEV','ORD 17-204','ECON_DEV_REDEV AFF_HOUS_REDEV ZONE_USE_AMEND The agenda item describes an ordinance that involves approving an amendment to a redevelopment agreement. This is closely aligned with the "ECON_DEV_REDEV" category, which is focused on redevelopment projects aimed at revitalizing commercial areas and supporting local business expansion. The description mentions a redevelopment agreement between the village and a developer, which signifies an economic development initiative using redevelopment strategies. This makes "ECON_DEV_REDEV" the most suitable first choice.','AD. ORD 17-204 An Ordinance Approving a Third Amendment to the Redevelopment Agreement to the Redevelopment Agreement Between the Village of Oak Park and OP South Boulevard LLC and Authorizing its Execution','782d09ad-1ddb-4db1-90a6-c0ca1a4b2495',33,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('AD. ORD 17-204 An Ordinance Approving a Third Amendment to the Redevelopment\nAgreement to the Redevelopment Agreement Between the Village of Oak\nPark and OP South Boulevard LLC and Authorizing its Execution\nVillage Manager Pavlicek stated that this ordinance provides for timing amendments\nwithin the Redevelopment Agreement for the property at Harlem and South Boulevard.\nThe Village had anticipated closing on the land and issuing building permits shortly after\nthe first of this year. Staff has been working with the developer to bring an extension of\nthat to the Board. She noted that there were Board Meetings in March that were\ncancelled and that is why it is coming to the Board at this time.\nDirector of Development Customer Services Tammie Grossman explained that upon\nlooking at some of their construction costs associated with the building, the developer is\nexploring alternate means of construction. That necessitates resubmitting the building\npermit application, including drawings. It will take some time for the developer to submit\nthese as well as Development Customer Services to review them. Ms. Grossman believed\nthat the dates set forth in the amendment are outside dates at best; closing should be\nwithin the next two months.\nDeveloper Joe Segobiano and Ms. Grossman answered questions from the Board.\nVillage President Abu-Taleb discussed the penalty of $75,000 if they do not close by\nJune 29. Mr. Segobiano assured the Board he would close by that day or sooner and\nspoke highly of his experience working with staff.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Lueck, seconded by Village Trustee Brewer, that\nthis Ordinance be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the vote\nwas as follows:\nAYES: 6 - Village Trustee Button, Village Trustee Taglia, Mayor Abu-Taleb, Village Trustee\nBrewer, Village Trustee Barber, and Village Trustee Lueck\nNAYS: 0\nABSENT: 1 - Village Trustee Tucker\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(360,4002,1605,'ENV_SUS_CLIM','MOT 17-167','ENV_SUS_CLIM ENV_SUS_PLST ENV_SUS_ENERGY The chosen classification, ENV_SUS_CLIM, is based on the agenda item''s focus on establishing an environmental community organization. This indicates a commitment to addressing environmental issues which typically align with climate action, sustainability, and possibly reducing environmental impacts at a broader level. The mention of "environmental" and the formation of an organization dedicated to it strongly suggest that the primary objective is likely aligned with climate action and sustainability goals.','AE. MOT 17-167 A Motion to Reject all Proposals for Consulting Services Related to the Proposed Formation of an Intergovernmental Environmental Community Organization or i-ECO and Direct Staff to Prepare the Necessary Actions to Establish a Full-Time Susta','05d701b0-9461-457c-845c-01cb4914c542',33,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-10-28T01:59:44',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(361,5607,1565,'ENV_SUS_PLST','ORD 17-203','```plaintext ENV_SUS_PLST ENV_SUS_RECY PUB_HLT_SERV ``` ### Explanation: The first choice, "ENV_SUS_PLST," is selected because the agenda item pertains to a pilot program focusing on retail single-use bags. This topic aligns most closely with issues of plastic reduction and efforts to minimize the use of single-use plastics, which is the primary concern addressed in the "ENV_SUS_PLST" category. The mention of "Plastic reduction and single-use plastic bans" makes it the best fit for this agenda item.','AF. ORD 17-203 An Ordinance Amending Chapter 20 ("Public Health") of the Oak Park Village Code to Add a New Article 14  - ("Retail Single-Use Bag Pilot Program")','61c1bfbf-263d-4c60-9476-fdd8ee715c16',33,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('AF. ORD 17-203 An Ordinance Amending Chapter 20 (“Public Health”) of the Oak Park\nVillage Code to Add a New Article 14 - (“Retail Single-Use Bag Pilot\nProgram”)\nVillage Manager Pavlicek stated that in May of 2014, Village Trustee Lueck asked that\nthe Environment and Energy Commission (EEC) review Chicago''s newly adopted\nordinance relative to banning plastic bags. After discussions and recommendations, the\nordinance was drafted similar to Chicago''s second version that imposes a bag tax. The\nordinance is meant to be a pilot program in effect for two years and will allow a six month\nperiod to be reviewed by the EEC after the first year. They would then make their\nrecommendations to the Village Board, who would have three months to make a decision\nbefore the end of the program. This will be a voluntary program and would only be offered\nto retailers over 5,000 sq. ft. They would require that anyone asking for any single use\nbag, paper or plastic, pay a ten cent fee. The retailer would keep half and half would be\nreturned to the Village, to be used to market those retailers as green partners, as well as\nretain these funds for other sustainable activities. In addition to the EEC, this was\ndiscussed with the Business Associations Council; there are diverse opinions on this\ntopic.\nEmily DiFrisco, representing Plastic Pollution Coalition. Ms. DiFrisco spoke in favor of\nthe ordinance, although she preferred banning plastic bags altogether.\nMr. Bridge spoke about problems caused by plastic bags. He compared eliminating\nsingle use bags to other behavioral issues that people have adapted to such as picking\nup after a pet and not smoking indoors. He and the commission did not recommend\nmaking this voluntary, although they were in agreement that it should apply to only the\nlarger retailers. Carolyn Cullen, member of the EEC, and Staff Liaison Karen Rozmus\nexplained why the commission recommend this be mandated rather than voluntary.\nVillage Trustee Lueck noted that there was no information regarding discussions held\nwith the EEC and that there is no incentive for retailers to participate. There was a\ndiscussion regarding that as well as the possible effects on lower income consumers.\nMs. Rozmus and Village Manager Pavlicek answered questions from the Board.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Button Ott, seconded by Village Trustee Brewer,\nthat this Ordinance be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the\nvote was as follows:\nAYES: 5 - Village Trustee Button, Village Trustee Taglia, Mayor Abu-Taleb, Village Trustee\nBrewer, and Village Trustee Barber\nNAYS: 1 - Village Trustee Lueck\nABSENT: 1 - Village Trustee Tucker\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
