INSERT INTO items VALUES(877,50,2302,'TRANS_INF_PARK','MOT 17-145','TRANS_INF_PARK PUB_WRK_PARK ZONE_USE_COMM The agenda item focuses on a motion concerning the guiding principles, goals, and schedule for reviewing and discussing public parking systems in Oak Park. The best fit for this classification is "TRANS_INF_PARK," which deals with parking lot management and parking infrastructure improvements, including new parking zones. This classification is chosen because the description of the agenda item directly relates to managing and improving public parking systems, which aligns with the focus of TRANS_INF_PARK.','A. MOT 17-145 Motion Approving Guiding Principles, Goals and Schedule for the Review and Discussion of the Public Parking Systems in Oak Park','2a2820e6-8979-4940-8591-04ce523935d4',77,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-10-28T01:59:44',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(878,2352,2150,'TRANS_INF_PARK','ID 17-366','TRANS_INF_PARK ZONE_USE_COMM PUB_ENG_HEAR The choice of TRANS_INF_PARK as the primary classification is because the agenda item specifically involves a study related to permit parking. This directly aligns with parking infrastructure improvements and management, including the creation and regulation of new parking zones, as described in the TRANS_INF_PARK category. In this context, the focus of the agenda item on "Overnight Permit Parking Study" suggests efforts to manage existing parking resources and address community needs in specific zones, which fits well under TRANS_INF_PARK.','B. ID 17-366 Review of the Transportation Commission Recommendations Related to Overnight Permit Parking Study in the Pleasant Business District and Gwendolyn Brooks Middle School Area Also Referred to As the Y2, Y3, and Y4 Zone.','fc28b831-f1b2-433c-a083-3032ef9d9e0a',77,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-10-28T01:59:44',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(879,4502,101,'PUB_WRK_ROADS','RES 17-456','PUB_WRK_ROADS PUB_WRK_UTIL ZONE_USE_AMEND The first choice, PUB_WRK_ROADS, was made because the agenda item involves a public sidewalk easement agreement. This suggests a focus on public infrastructure related to pedestrian pathways, which aligns with issues of road and street maintenance, as sidewalks are often part of broader roadway projects and maintenance plans. The classification suggests that this item involves considerations similar to resurfacing and traffic calming, as it pertains to the village''s planning and maintenance of public walkways.','C. RES 17-456 A Resolution Approving a Public Sidewalk Easement Agreement Between the Village of Oak Park and WDF-3 Wood Oak Park Owner, LLC and Authorizing its Execution','ddbd5317-b839-4f47-b698-0f1f2e60bac8',77,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('C. RES 17-456 A Resolution Approving a Public Sidewalk Easement Agreement Between\nthe Village of Oak Park and WDF-3 Wood Oak Park Owner, LLC and\nAuthorizing its Execution\nVillage Manager Pavlicek stated that this and the next two Items are all specific actions\nto effectuate the finalization of the redevelopment agreement as amended between the\nVillage of Oak Park and WDF-3 Wood. This agreement provides that the sidewalk\nconstructed on Lake Street by WDF-3 Wood will be open for public use and obligates the\nVillage to provide ongoing maintenance of the sidewalk.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Tucker, seconded by Village Trustee Barber,\nthat this Resolution be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the\nvote was as follows:\nAYES: 5 - Village Trustee Salzman, Village President Abu-Taleb, Village Trustee Brewer,\nVillage Trustee Barber, and Village Trustee Tucker\nNAYS: 0\nABSENT: 2 - Village Trustee Button Ott, and Village Trustee Lueck\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(880,4603,268,'TRANS_INF_PARK','RES 17-455','``` TRANS_INF_PARK PUB_WRK_PARK FIN_MGT_BUDGET ``` The agenda item primarily deals with the budget amendment for the construction of a parking garage. The mention of the parking garage at a specific location directly relates to the classification of "TRANS_INF_PARK," which involves parking lot management and infrastructure improvements. This classification captures the essence of the agenda, focusing on the construction and budgetary aspects attached to parking infrastructure.','D. RES 17-455 A Resolution Approving an Amendment to the Project Budget for the Construction of the Public Portion of the Parking Garage at 150 Forest Avenue and the Use of Owner Contingency for Final Change Orders in the Amount of $92,028.29','42f9403b-5ed3-4cc0-8987-e13dc3d8afab',77,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('D. RES 17-455 A Resolution Approving an Amendment to the Project Budget for the\nConstruction of the Public Portion of the Parking Garage at 150 Forest\nAvenue and the Use of Owner Contingency for Final Change Orders in the\nAmount of $92,028.29\nVillage Manager Pavlicek clarified that this expenditure is for interest costs for the project\nfinancing for the month of January and change orders related to design modifications\nrequired fire safety, ADA requirements, etc.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Tucker, seconded by Village Trustee Salzman,\nthat this Resolution be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the\nvote was as follows:\nAYES: 6 - Village Trustee Salzman, Village President Abu-Taleb, Village Trustee Button Ott,\nVillage Trustee Brewer, Village Trustee Barber, and Village Trustee Tucker\nNAYS: 0\nABSENT: 1 - Village Trustee Lueck\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(881,4871,60,'ZONE_USE_AMEND','ORD 17-170','ZONE_USE_AMEND ZONE_USE_RES ZONE_USE_PERMIT The agenda item appears to pertain to the approval of a subdivision plat, which often involves amending existing zoning ordinances or regulations to accommodate new land use configurations. The classification "ZONE_USE_AMEND" relates to zoning ordinance amendments, making it a suitable fit as the agenda item likely requires alterations or endorsements of current zoning provisions to approve the subdivision plat.','E. ORD 17-170 An Ordinance Approving a Vertical Subdivision Plat for the Lake and Forest Subdivision','01d2d1fb-eb22-4a7a-aae9-09d3e69d8015',77,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-10-28T01:59:44',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(882,4931,452,'PUB_WRK_ROADS','ID 17-406','PUB_WRK_ROADS PUB_WRK_UTIL TRANS_INF_TRAFFIC The agenda item titled "17-406 F. ID 17-406 Update on the FY18 Resurfacing, Utlity and Streetscape Work Scheduled for Lake Street" prominently features resurfacing work, which falls directly under the description for PUB_WRK_ROADS. It includes aspects related to road and street maintenance, thereby making it the most suitable classification. Furthermore, the mention of utility work aligns with PUB_WRK_UTIL, and streetscape work could potentially involve traffic-related improvements, justifying the choice of TRANS_INF_TRAFFIC as a possible fit. However, resurfacing is the primary focus and guides the classification choice.','F. ID 17-406 Update on the FY18 Resurfacing, Utlity and Streetscape Work Scheduled for Lake Street','f9532164-27a7-49e6-8ee9-22bcf0509584',77,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('F. ID 17-406 Update on the FY18 Resurfacing, Utlity and Streetscape Work Scheduled\nfor Lake Street\nVillage Manager Pavlicek stated that the Capital Improvement Plan includes replacement\nof infrastructure along Lake Street. Some is simple asphalt paving, some is underground\nutility work for water and sewer and some is above ground work primarily from the curb to\nthe sidewalk. Some areas will look like the new area around Lake and Forest with\nbluestone and there will also be improvements to landscaped planters. Because staff has\nidentified some Federal funding sources for that work, they are required to begin a\nprocess that includes putting notice in the newspaper and holding public meetings. She\nwanted the Board to be made aware of that.\nVillage Engineer Bill McKenna gave a brief overview of the projected timeline for the\nprocess. He and Village Manager Pavlicek and answered questions from the Board.\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
