INSERT INTO items VALUES(1380,2132,518,'AFF_HOUS_DEV','MOT 17-178','AFF_HOUS_DEV AFF_HOUS_REDEV ZONE_USE_RES The first classification, "AFF_HOUS_DEV," was chosen because the agenda item involves discussions related to a school addition, which typically falls under development-related initiatives. While the agenda item specifically mentions "District 97" and "Holmes School," implying educational institutions, these projects often include planning and development functions that align with the creation or expansion of structures and facilities. Given the nature of the proposed addition, it can be categorized alongside initiatives like housing development projects, even though the exact focus here is educational rather than residential. The emphasis on development and infrastructure improvements naturally leads to this classification.','A. MOT 17-178 Motion Supporting District 97''s (D97) Discussions Related to the Proposed Holmes School Addition','61f46263-a191-47d7-9484-2eac5a688d34',120,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-10-28T01:59:44',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(1381,2650,5205,'ZONE_USE_AMEND','ID 17-467','ZONE_USE_AMEND ZONE_USE_COMM ZONE_USE_RES The agenda item is primarily concerned with presenting revisions to a zoning ordinance and zoning map, necessitating direction for staff to prepare an ordinance. This aligns most closely with the category "ZONE_USE_AMEND," which covers zoning ordinance amendments, as the item''s main focus is on reviewing and updating the Oak Park zoning regulations. The inclusion of the zoning map and request for steps towards ordinance preparation also supports this classification as it implies significant changes to existing regulations.','D. ID 17-467 Presentation of the Revised Oak Park Zoning Ordinance and a Revised Oak Park Zoning Map as Reviewed by the Oak Park Plan Commission and a Request for Direction for Staff to Prepare the Necessary Ordinance','e5c6774e-3051-4bba-9e9b-e6279cb612c9',120,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('D. ID 17-467 Presentation of the Revised Oak Park Zoning Ordinance and a Revised Oak\nPark Zoning Map as Reviewed by the Oak Park Plan Commission and a\nRequest for Direction for Staff to Prepare the Necessary Ordinance\nVillage Manager Pavlicek stated that in 2013, the most recent Comprehensive Plan was\nadopted by the Village Board. One of the tasks established in the Plan was a\ncomprehensive update to the Zoning Ordinance. She noted that this is a very substantive\ndocument and staff would like the Board to take as much time as they need to go\nthrough it and provide direction.\nVillage Planner Craig Failor stated that one of the things that municipalities do after\nadopting a new Comprehensive Plan is look at the regulatory documents and planning\nstudies to determine whether or not they conform with the Plan. He reiterated that the\nPlan included a recommendation to review the Zoning Code to see if it is still valid and\nconforms with the Plan. Mr. Failor gave a summary of the process that included working\nwith the Plan Commission and consultants and described the extensive public outreach\nand the many public meetings and public hearings. Tonight''s presentation is what they\nhave come up with, which was endorsed by the Plan Commission.\nArista Stungys of Camiros stated that the ideal time to update a Zoning Ordinance is\nafter adopting an updated Comprehensive Plan. She discussed how the two relate to\neach other. The presentation is compartmentalized into Introduction, Districts, Design,\nUses, On-Site Development, Administration and Implementation.\nChris Jennette of Camiros discussed changes made in the Residential District\nregulations. The Commercial District structure has been completely reorganized. The\nDowntown District has been divided into sub-districts; DT-1 Downtown Central, DT 2\nHemingway and DT3 Pleasant. Use restrictions have been implemented into DT1 and\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
