INSERT INTO items VALUES(2011,795,4,'PUB_ENG_CITIZEN','MOT 15-108','PUB_ENG_CITIZEN PROC_ELECTIONS PUB_ENG_MEET The first choice, PUB_ENG_CITIZEN, was selected due to the nature of the agenda item, which involves appointments to citizen oversight initiatives such as the Citizen Police Oversight Committee. This directly aligns with the category description of citizen oversight initiatives, making it the most suitable classification for this agenda item.','C. MOT 15-108 Motion to consent to the Village President''s Appointment of: Citizen Police Oversight Committee - Andreen Neukranz-Butler, Appoint as Chair Citizen Police Oversight Committee - John Nowicki, Appoint as Member Plan Commission - Kristin Nordman','819dc597-ad88-4212-b03a-1dccf05cd06e',169,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('C. MOT 15-108 Motion to consent to the Village President’s Appointment of:\nCitizen Police Oversight Committee - Andreen Neukranz-Butler, Appoint as\nChair\nCitizen Police Oversight Committee - John Nowicki, Appoint as Member\nPlan Commission - Kristin Nordman, Appoint as Member\nTransportation Commission - Mark Patzloff, Reappoint as Member\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Tucker, seconded by Village Trustee Barber,\nthat this Motion be approved. A voice vote was taken and the motion was\napproved.\n','\n',char(10)),1);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(2012,799,601,'PROC','ORD 15-157','PROC_ORD_RULES PROC_VILLAGE_RULES PROC_VILLAGE_POLICY The primary reason for classifying the agenda item under PROC_ORD_RULES as the best fit is due to its description: "First Reading of an Ordinance Amending Chapter 4 (''Ambulances''), Article 1 (''Ambulance Regulations''), Section 4-1-6 (''Village Ambulance Services; Fees'') of the Oak Park Village Code and Adding a New Section 9-1-16 (''Pipeline and Power Line In...". This directly involves modifying existing ordinances, which falls squarely under procedural rules that guide the adoption, modification, and repeal of municipal laws. The reference to the reading of an ordinance and amendments to specific sections strongly indicate a legislative procedure concerning ordinance rules.','D. ORD 15-157 First Reading of an Ordinance Amending Chapter 4 ("Ambulances"), Article 1 ("Ambulance Regulations"), Section 4-1-6 ("Village Ambulance Services; Fees") of the Oak Park Village Code and Adding a New Section 9-1-16 ("Pipeline and Power Line In','7690c2bf-7b33-41b1-b3b8-3b073d98055a',169,'2024-10-28T01:59:44','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('D. ORD 15-157 First Reading of an Ordinance Amending Chapter 4 (“Ambulances”), Article\n1 (“Ambulance Regulations”), Section 4-1-6 (“Village Ambulance Services;\nFees”) of the Oak Park Village Code and Adding a New Section 9-1-16\n(“Pipeline and Power Line Incidents”) to the Village Code\nVillage Manager Pavlicek stated that this ordinance would update the fees the Village\ncharges for ambulance services. This revenue source is used to pay for the operating\nequipment and any disposable materials used.\nFire Chief Tom Ebsen stated that the Fire Department provides emergency medical\nservices to the community and charge a fee for that. the fees vary depending on whether\nit is for a resident or non-resident and also upon the nature of the call. A minor call is\ncategorized as a basic life support incident. A major EMS call , such as a heart attack or\ntrauma, that requires advanced life saving techniques is categorized separately and billed\nhigher due to the extra service that is provided. Results from the 2014 survey of fees\nperformed by Naperville and completed by 118 municipalities in the Chicagoland area\nindicated that Oak Park''s fees are below average. This increase will make the Village\ncompetitive with other municipalities.\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
