INSERT INTO items VALUES(2253,2930,1331,'FIN_MGT_TAX','ORD 17-277','FIN_MGT_TAX FIN_MGT_BUDGET FIN_MGT_GRANTS The first choice, "FIN_MGT_TAX," was selected primarily because the agenda item involves the issuance of general obligation bonds, which typically require the levy and collection of taxes to service the debt. The description of "FIN_MGT_TAX" fits well as it involves tax levy ordinances and fiscal management ensuring adequate funding for municipal services, which aligns closely with issuing bonds and managing the associated tax requirements.','AC. ORD 17-277 An Ordinance Providing for a Not-To-Exceed Issuance of $13,700,000 General Obligation Corporate Purpose Bonds, Series 2017A, of the Village of Oak Park, Cook County, Illinois, and Providing for the Levy and Collection of a Direct Annual Tax','9b84102a-6fbc-43d1-b2ea-43e7f8d9c2d5',186,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-10-28T01:59:45',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(2254,4261,146,'FIN_MGT_BUDGET','ORD 17-278','FIN_MGT_BUDGET FIN_MGT_TAX FIN_MGT_GRANTS The first choice, FIN_MGT_BUDGET, was made because the agenda item discusses an ordinance involving the issuance of general obligation refunding bonds. This pertains to managing the village''s financial obligations and capital structure, which is inherently related to budget discussions and the overall fiscal strategy. The mention of the levy and collection indicates a focus on how these funds will be acquired and managed, which fits broadly within budgeting considerations.','AD. ORD 17-278 An Ordinance Providing for a Not-To-Exceed Issuance of $4,500,000 General Obligation Corporate Purpose Refunding Bonds, Series 2017B and 2017C, of the Village of Oak Park, Cook County, Illinois, and Providing for the Levy and Collection of a','2b9cb29f-8b17-4eae-b61b-b27581ab5442',186,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('AD. ORD 17-278 An Ordinance Providing for a Not-To-Exceed Issuance of $4,500,000 General\nObligation Corporate Purpose Refunding Bonds, Series 2017B and 2017C, of\nthe Village of Oak Park, Cook County, Illinois, and Providing for the Levy\nand Collection of a Direct Annual Tax for the Payment of the Principal of\nand Interest on Said Bonds\nVillage Manager Pavlicek stated that this item is for refunding two prior bond issues. The\nVillage will receive the actual numbers in approximately two weeks. If the numbers do\nnote reflect the $88,000 in savings that they anticipate, staff will come back to the Board.\nOtherwise, the ordinance authorizes that the transaction be completed.\nMr. McCanna explained why this cannot happen today as a result of the bond issuance\nthat was just approved.\nVillage Trustee Button clarified for the public that the term "refunding" means refinaning at\na lower rate.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Button, seconded by Village Trustee Tucker, that\nthis Ordinance be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the vote\nwas as follows:\nAYES: 7 - Village Trustee Button, Village Trustee Taglia, Village President Abu-Taleb, Village\nTrustee Tucker, Village Trustee Moroney, Village Trustee Boutet, and Village\nTrustee Andrews\nNAYS: 0\nABSENT: 0\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(2255,4407,1410,'PUB_HLT_SERV','RES 17-648','PUB_HLT_SERV PUB_ENG_HEAR PUB_ENG_MEET The reason for choosing PUB_HLT_SERV as the best fit is due to the agenda item''s primary focus on a community health plan. The item describes the approval and submission of the Illinois Project for Local Assessment of Needs (IPLAN) Five Year Community Health Plan, which directly pertains to evaluations and planning of community health needs. This aligns closely with the description of essential public health services, making PUB_HLT_SERV the most relevant classification.','AE. RES 17-648 A Resolution Approving the 2017 Illinois Project for Local Assessment of Needs (IPLAN) Five Year Community Health Plan and Authorizing Submission of the IPLAN to the Illinois Department of Public Health','1768472d-8f9f-4dfa-88ac-dbaba581585f',186,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-10-28T01:59:45',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(2256,5817,2546,'TRANS_INF_TRAFFIC','MOT 17-216','TRANS_INF_TRAFFIC PUB_WRK_ROADS TRANS_INF_TRANS The agenda item "17-216 AF. MOT 17-216 A Motion to Reject the Transportation Commission''s Recommendations for the Use of a Traffic Calming Toolbox to be used in the Development and Implementation of a Neighborhood Traffic Management Program for Residential Streets" is classified under TRANS_INF_TRAFFIC as the best fit. The reasoning for this choice is that the agenda item is focused on "Traffic Calming" measures, which directly relates to traffic-related issues like implementing strategies to manage traffic flow and safety on residential streets. This classification aligns with the detailed description provided for TRANS_INF_TRAFFIC, which includes considerations such as traffic calming measures.','AF. MOT 17-216 A Motion to Reject  the Transportation Commission''s Recommendations for the Use of a Traffic Calming Toolbox to be used in the Development and Implementation of a Neighborhood Traffic Management Program for Residential Streets','1fc42876-1102-48f5-9595-ec30c5a4e67d',186,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-10-28T01:59:45',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(2257,8363,1467,'TRANS_INF_TRAFFIC','MOT 17-248','TRANS_INF_TRAFFIC TRAN_INF_EXP PUB_ENG_HEAR The first choice, TRANS_INF_TRAFFIC, is made because the agenda item clearly pertains to traffic-related issues, specifically the discussion and consideration of the installation of speed tables or bumps. These measures are commonly associated with traffic calming and road safety, which aligns directly with the description of the TRANS_INF_TRAFFIC category.','AG. MOT 17-248 A Motion to Reject the Transportation Commission''s Recommendation to Install Speed Tables or Bumps on the 1200 Blocks of Columbian, North Euclid, Linden, and North East Avenues','cebf8c2b-059c-4c2f-b2fe-d797b6c19e21',186,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-10-28T01:59:45',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(2258,9830,386,'STAFF_MGMT_HIRE','RES 17-660','STAFF_MGMT_HIRE STAFF_MGMT_COMP OTHER The first choice "STAFF_MGMT_HIRE" was made because the agenda item involves the approval of an employment-related resolution — specifically, an employee leasing agreement for a temporary position. This fits under the category of hiring and recruitment matters within municipal departments. The involvement of a temporary assistant director indicates a staffing requirement, aligning well with hiring and recruitment needs.','AH. RES 17-660 A Resolution Approving an Employee Leasing Agreement for a Temporary Development Customer Services Assistant Director with GovTemps USA, LLC and Authorizing its Execution','dd39e087-1982-422a-91c3-4bcd1eafe929',186,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('AH. RES 17-660 A Resolution Approving an Employee Leasing Agreement for a Temporary\nDevelopment Customer Services Assistant Director with GovTemps USA,\nLLC and Authorizing its Execution\nVillage Manager Pavlicek noted that when the Board approved adding the Parking Division\nto Development Customer Services, staff recommended that the Parking Director position\nbe eliminated and replaced with the position of Assistant Director of Development\nCustomer Services. During the recruitment process, staff would like to use temporary\nservices. The individual is a retired City Manager of Evanston, who is providing a\nsignificant amount of assistance to Director Grossman.\nVillage Trustee Boutet commented that although GovTemps and GovHR provide a\nvaluable service, they are overused and negatively affect employee morale. She stated\nthat an existing competent staff person should be used and that temps fill lower level\npositions.\nVillage Trustee Andrews agreed, however, this is the Manager''s decision.\nVillage Trustee Button appreciates that Director Grossman needs the assistance;\nTrustee Tucker agreed.\nVillage President Abu-Taleb disagreed with Village Trustee Boutet, as there are times\nwhen the temporary person could end up being the permanent person. It is good\nbusiness practice.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Taglia, seconded by Village Trustee Button, that\nthis Resolution be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the vote\nwas as follows:\nAYES: 6 - Village Trustee Button, Village Trustee Taglia, Village President Abu-Taleb, Village\nTrustee Tucker, Village Trustee Moroney, and Village Trustee Andrews\nNAYS: 1 - Village Trustee Boutet\nABSENT: 0\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(2259,10216,254,'PROC','ORD 17-297','PROC_ORD_RULES PROC_VILLAGE_RULES ZONE_USE_AMEND The primary choice, PROC_ORD_RULES, was made because the agenda item involves the first reading of an ordinance, which typically relates to the procedural rules involved in amending municipal laws. This includes changes to existing ordinances regarding liquor licenses, emphasizing the legislative process that governs the adoption and modification of these laws. The item specifically references amendments to ordinance sections, which aligns with the procedural nature of this classification.','AK. ORD 17-297 First Reading of an Ordinance Amending Chapter 3 ("Alcoholic Liquor Dealers"), Section 3-4-2 ("Classification and Number of Liquor Licenses and Fees"), Section 3-8-1 ("Number of Licenses Permitted to be Issued") and Section 3-8-2 ("Licenses','de1756c2-d107-4372-baa6-05fa2096717b',186,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('AK. ORD 17-297 First Reading of an Ordinance Amending Chapter 3 (“Alcoholic Liquor\nDealers”), Section 3-4-2 (“Classification and Number of Liquor Licenses and\nFees”), Section 3-8-1 (“Number of Licenses Permitted to be Issued”) and\nSection 3-8-2 (“Licenses by Name and Address Per License”) of the Oak Park\nVillage Code Regarding Liquor License Annual Fees and the Names and\nNumbers of Current Licensees\nVillage Attorney Stephanides stated that the Liquor Control Review Board has been\nworking on this for quite some time. The ordinance amends the annual fees for Class\nB-1, B-2, B-3 and B-4 Restaurant Licenses, Class C-1 Package License, Class D-16\nCraft Brew Lounge License and Special Event Licenses. Restaurants would be on a tier\nsystem based upon the number of seats and the others have been changed to be\ncompetitive with the surrounding communities. The ordinance also amends the names\nand numbers of the licensees to be in line with the current names and numbers of license\nholders. The Local Liquor Commissioner, Village Trustee Button, concurs with the\nrecommendations.\nVillage Trustee Button commented that Oak Park''s fees are so disproportionate to\nEvanston''s and asked why that is so. Village Attorney Stephanides stated that the\nVillage''s fees would be more in line with Berwyn and Skokie with the amendment and\nacknowledged that they have been on the low side.\nVillage Trustee Tagila asked if the businesses were consulted regarding the fee changes.\nVillage Attorney Stephanides stated that they have, and that is how the tiered approach\ncame about.\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(2260,10470,109,'PROC','ORD 17-294','PROC_ORD_RULES ZONE_USE_AMEND PROC_BOARD_RULES The first choice, PROC_ORD_RULES, was made because the agenda item involves an ordinance that amends sections related to the issuance and classification of licenses for alcoholic liquor dealers. This is clearly about procedural rules guiding the modification of existing municipal laws, which matches perfectly with the description provided for PROC_ORD_RULES.','AL. ORD 17-294 An Ordinance Amending Chapter 3 ("Alcoholic Liquor Dealers"), Article 8 ("List of Licenses for Each License Class"), Section 3-8-1 ("Number of Licenses to be Issued Per LIcence Class") and Section 3-8-2 ("Licenses by Name and Address Per Lic','ee086541-022c-4bd0-b3ef-e3dda05ce478',186,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('AL. ORD 17-294 An Ordinance Amending Chapter 3 (“Alcoholic Liquor Dealers”), Article 8\n(“List of Licenses for Each License Class”), Section 3-8-1 (“Number of\nLicenses to be Issued Per LIcence Class”) and Section 3-8-2 (“Licenses by\nName and Address Per License”) of the Oak Park Village Code for the\nIssuance of a Restaurant Class B-1 Liquor License to District Kitchen & Tap,\nInc.\nVillage Attorney Stephanides stated that District Kitchen & Tap, Inc. is another location\nby the owner of Scratch Kitchen. The Liquor Control Review Board unanimously approved\nrecommendation for the license.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Andrews, seconded by Village Trustee Tucker,\nthat this Ordinance be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the\nvote was as follows:\nAYES: 6 - Village Trustee Button, Village Trustee Taglia, Village Trustee Tucker, Village\nTrustee Moroney, Village Trustee Boutet, and Village Trustee Andrews\nNAYS: 0\nABSENT: 0\nABSTAINED: 1 - Village President Abu-Taleb\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
