INSERT INTO items VALUES(2440,5118,671,'ZONE_USE_PERMIT','ORD 16-128','ZONE_USE_PERMIT ZONE_USE_COMM ZONE_USE_RES The first choice, ZONE_USE_PERMIT, was made because the agenda item involves adopting an ordinance to grant a variance from existing use restrictions in a specific zoning area. This fits the description of special use permits for businesses and housing developments within the municipality, as it deals with granting permissions that deviate from the established zoning rules to allow a specific commercial activity (operating a general office for State Farm Insurance) within the Transit-Related Retail Overlay District.','W. ORD 16-128 Concur with the Zoning Board of Appeals'' Recommendations and Adopt An Ordinance Granting a Variance from the Transit-Related Retail Overlay District''s Use Restrictions to Operate a General Office Use (State Farm Insurance) at 177 S. Oak Park','5173a905-856a-411f-b97f-db98aeb6c652',204,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-10-28T01:59:45',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(2441,5789,284,'PUB_HLT_SERV','ORD 16-129','PUB_HLT_SERV PROC_ORD_RULES ENV_SUS_PLST **Explanation:** The agenda item primarily deals with amendments to public health ordinances, specifically focused on environmental health services (home kitchen and cottage food operations). Therefore, it best fits the classification PUB_HLT_SERV, as it involves essential public health services and community health needs evaluations. This code represents the broader implications of introducing regulations related to food operations under the public health domain.','L. ORD 16-129 An Ordinance Amending Chapter 20 ("Public Health"), Article 3 ("Environmental Health Services") of the Oak Park Village Code by Adding a New Section 20-3-13 ("Home Kitchen and Cottage Food Operations")','21383f7f-eb9b-4a5f-9591-8586c2bad501',204,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('L. ORD 16-129 An Ordinance Amending Chapter 20 ("Public Health"), Article 3\n(“Environmental Health Services”) of the Oak Park Village Code by Adding\na New Section 20-3-13 (“Home Kitchen and Cottage Food Operations”)\nVillage Manager Pavlicek noted that at a recent meeting, the Board had a request to\nallow the sale of home baked goods out of one''s home. The Village Attorney and Health\nDirector looked at the statutory items that the Village needed to adopt and incorporated\nprovisions of the Illinois Food Handling Enforcement Act, "Home Kitchen Operations" and\n"Cottage Food Operations" into the ordinance.\nVillage Attorney Paul Stephanides clarified that labeling of ingredients is required. Interim\nHealth Director Mike Charley also noted that the Cottage Food Operations provision\nallows the sale of such items at the Farmers'' Market.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Tucker, seconded by Village Trustee Barber,\nthat this Ordinance be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the\nvote was as follows:\nAYES: 6 - Village Trustee Abu-Taleb, Village Trustee Button Ott, Village Trustee Lueck,\nVillage Trustee Brewer, Village Trustee Barber, and Village Trustee Tucker\nNAYS: 0\nABSENT: 1 - Village Trustee Salzman\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(2442,6073,433,'ZONE_USE_AMEND','RES 16-374','ZONE_USE_AMEND PUB_WRK_ROADS TRANS_INF_PARK The item "RES 16-374 A Resolution Approving an Amendment to the Project Budget for Oak Park Station to Include a Brick Alternate for Westgate from the New Maple Street East through the Cul-De-Sac, Removal of a Curb Cut on Lake Street Related to the Parking Lot" was classified primarily as ZONE_USE_AMEND because it involves amending a project budget and likely pertains to updates or modifications in zoning ordinances related to a specific area''s land use, in this case, a modification for Oak Park Station. The reference to specific streets and changes to infrastructure elements like curb cuts suggests a zoning or developmental change, which aligns with the ZONE_USE_AMEND category.','Y. RES 16-374 A Resolution Approving an Amendment to the Project Budget for Oak Park Station to Include a Brick Alternate for Westgate from the New Maple Street East through the Cul-De-Sac, Removal of a Curb Cut on Lake Street Related to the Parking Lot an','6efd13e0-be35-4ea2-b056-9e275838a7ae',204,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-10-28T01:59:45',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(2443,6506,253,'ZONE_USE_AMEND','ORD 16-135','ZONE_USE_AMEND PROC_ORD_RULES PROC_VILLAGE_POLICY The agenda item appears to primarily involve amending an ordinance, which likely fits under ZONE_USE_AMEND (Zoning ordinance amendments to update regulations on land use and business operations) because it involves changes to the municipal code, specifically regarding the regulation and issuance of licenses. While it''s not directly a zoning issue, the symbolic name suggests it covers ordinance amendments more broadly. Thus, the focus on ordinance amendment aligns with what ZONE_USE_AMEND covers, though should there have been a more suitable category, I would have considered it. Additionally, the procedural aspect of amending rules or guidelines aligns with PROC_ORD_RULES, which directly addresses ordinance procedures.','Z. ORD 16-135 An Ordinance Amending Chapter 3 ("Alcoholic Liquor Dealers"), Article 8 ("List of Licenses for Each License Class"), Section 3-8-1 ("Number of Licenses to be Issued Per License Class") and Section 3-8-2 ("Licenses by Name and Address Per Lice','e647d2be-4e51-4da2-b4cf-f8d679c0b4c8',204,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('Z. ORD 16-135 An Ordinance Amending Chapter 3 (“Alcoholic Liquor Dealers”), Article 8\n(“List of Licenses for Each License Class”), Section 3-8-1 (“Number of\nLicenses to be Issued Per License Class”) and Section 3-8-2 (“Licenses by\nName and Address Per License”) of the Oak Park Village Code for the\nIssuance of a Restaurant Class B-2 Liquor License and a Package Class C-1\nLiquor License to LJC Development, LLC, d/b/a Lea French Street Food\nThe owner of Lea French Street Food spoke about the restaurant, which will serve\nbreakfast, lunch and dinner. Liquor Commission Chair Victoria Scaman spoke in favor of\ngranting the license.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Button Ott, seconded by Village Trustee Barber,\nthat this Ordinance be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the\nvote was as follows:\nAYES: 4 - Village Trustee Button Ott, Village Trustee Lueck, Village Trustee Barber, and\nVillage Trustee Tucker\nNAYS: 0\nABSENT: 1 - Village Trustee Salzman\nABSTAINED: 2 - Village Trustee Abu-Taleb, and Village Trustee Brewer\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(2444,6759,169,'PROC','ORD 16-136','PROC_ORD_RULES ZONE_USE_AMEND PROC_VILLAGE_RULES The first choice, PROC_ORD_RULES, was made because the agenda item is an ordinance amending specific chapters and sections related to alcoholic liquor dealer licenses. This fits within the scope of ordinance and procedural rules regarding the adoption, modification, and repeal of municipal laws. The ordinance specifically addresses changes to the number and specifics of liquor licenses, which is a procedural rule function.','AA. ORD 16-136 An Ordinance Amending Chapter 3 ("Alcoholic Liquor Dealers"), Article 8 ("List of Licenses for Each License Class"), Section 3-8-1 ("Number of Licenses to be Issued Per License Class") and Section 3-8-2 ("Licenses by Name and Address Per Lic','46770edf-fc34-4615-86dd-5e674874ec02',204,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-10-28T01:59:45',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(2445,6928,130,'ZONE_USE_AMEND','ORD 16-137','ZONE_USE_AMEND PROC_ORD_RULES OTHER The first choice, ZONE_USE_AMEND, was made because the agenda item involves amending a chapter related to liquor licenses, which falls under zoning ordinances and land use operations. Modifications to a legal document like this typically involve updates or changes to the existing regulations, fitting well with the classification of zoning ordinance amendments.','AB. ORD 16-137 An Ordinance Amending Chapter 3 ("Alcoholic Liquor Dealers"), Article 8 ("List of Licenses for Each License Class"), Section 3-8-1 ("Number of Licenses to be Issued Per License Class") and Section 3-8-2 ("Licenses by Name and Address Per Lic','5aeea89c-6fb7-4aeb-9bea-e276caa3cd8c',204,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('AB. ORD 16-137 An Ordinance Amending Chapter 3 (“Alcoholic Liquor Dealers”), Article 8\n(“List of Licenses for Each License Class”), Section 3-8-1 (“Number of\nLicenses to be Issued Per License Class”) and Section 3-8-2 (“Licenses by\nName and Address Per License”) of the Oak Park Village Code for the\nIssuance of a Restaurant Class B-1 Liquor License to Patrick Dailey and Olga\nDailey, DBA Eastgate Cafe\nMs. Scaman stated that there will be a small liquor selection, as there is no space for a\nbar and bar stools.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Button Ott, seconded by Village Trustee Lueck,\nthat this Ordinance be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the\nvote was as follows:\nAYES: 4 - Village Trustee Button Ott, Village Trustee Lueck, Village Trustee Barber, and\nVillage Trustee Tucker\nNAYS: 0\nABSENT: 1 - Village Trustee Salzman\nABSTAINED: 2 - Village Trustee Abu-Taleb, and Village Trustee Brewer\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
