INSERT INTO items VALUES(2750,1345,157,'PROC','RES 17-490','PROC_ELECTIONS PROC_VILLAGE_POLICY OTHER The agenda item titled "17-490 R. RES 17-490 Resolution Appointing the Local Liquor Control Commissioner" appears to be related to an official appointment process. This topic falls most closely under the category of PROC_ELECTIONS, which involves municipal elections, appointments, and electoral process management. This classification seems to match well because appointing a Local Liquor Control Commissioner involves procedural decisions and falls within the realm of governance and appointments that are crucial parts of the electoral process. The use of "Resolution Appointing" indicates this is a formal process of governance, closely aligning with appointment-related affairs covered under this symbolic name.','R. RES 17-490 Resolution Appointing the Local Liquor Control Commissioner','7049f7f3-df2c-47a5-abb3-f5bed1e72198',227,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('R. RES 17-490 Resolution Appointing the Local Liquor Control Commissioner\nVillage Attorney Paul Stephanides stated that this resolution appoints a successor to\nVillage Trustee Salzman, who has resigned as Local Liquor Control Commissioner\neffective February 22. This person must be an attorney who is licensed to practice in\nIllinois, pursuant to the Village Code. Historically, it has also been a member of the\nBoard of Trustees.\nPresident Pro Tem Salzman asked his colleagues for a nomination.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Tucker, seconded by Village Trustee Barber,\nthat Village Trustee Andrea Button Ott be appointed as Local Liquor Control\nCommissioner. The motion was approved. The roll call on the vote was as\nfollows:\nAYES: 4 - Village Trustee Salzman, Village Trustee Button Ott, Village Trustee Barber, and\nVillage Trustee Tucker\nNAYS: 0\nABSENT: 1 - Village Trustee Lueck\nRECUSED: 2 - Village President Abu-Taleb, and Village Trustee Brewer\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(2751,1502,294,'STAFF_MGMT_HIRE','RES 17-492','``` STAFF_MGMT_HIRE STAFF_MGMT_COMP PROC_VILLAGE_POLICY ``` The agenda item "17-492 O. RES 17-492 A Resolution Amending the Village Manager''s Employment Agreement" primarily pertains to human resources and municipal staffing management. It deals with the employment agreement of a key municipal executive, which falls under discussions related to hiring, recruitment, and staffing. Therefore, the best fit for this agenda item is "STAFF_MGMT_HIRE" as it directly points to issues surrounding employment agreements and contracts for municipal roles.','O. RES 17-492 A Resolution Amending the Village Manager''s Employment Agreement.','83f19a39-0850-4d0b-9d47-2d5a0db78ad0',227,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('O. RES 17-492 A Resolution Amending the Village Manager’s Employment Agreement.\nVillage Attorney Stephanides stated that this amendment to the Village Manager''s\nemployment agreement will increase her salary by $10,000 for the year 2017, pursuant to\nthe employment agreement and the Board''s direction.\nVillage Trustees Barber, Brewer and Button Ott gave positive feedback regarding Village\nManager Pavlicek''s performance. Village President Abu-Taleb commented that the\nVillage is lucky to have her and that the culture at Village Hall is now positive.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Salzman, seconded by Village Trustee Brewer,\nthat this Resolution be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the\nvote was as follows:\nAYES: 6 - Village Trustee Salzman, Village President Abu-Taleb, Village Trustee Button Ott,\nVillage Trustee Brewer, Village Trustee Barber, and Village Trustee Tucker\nNAYS: 0\nABSENT: 1 - Village Trustee Lueck\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(2752,1796,104,'PUB_WRK_UTIL','RES 17-493','PUB_WRK_UTIL ENV_SUS_CLIM PUB_HLT_SERV The best fit for the agenda item "17-493 Q. RES 17-493 A Resolution Approving Right of Entry Agreement with the Board of Education of Oak Park Elementary School District Number 97 for Performing Surveying and Environmental Inspections Near Kenilworth and Chicago" is PUB_WRK_UTIL because it involves an agreement to perform surveying and environmental inspections, which generally aligns with public works projects concerning utility infrastructure and improvements. Although the description specifically mentions water mains and drainage systems, environmental inspections could potentially relate to broader utility and infrastructure concerns.','Q. RES 17-493 A Resolution Approving Right of Entry Agreement with the Board of Education of Oak Park Elementary School District Number 97 for Performing Surveying and Environmental Inspections Near Kenilworth and Chicago','3c07c428-1030-42fd-8b9c-2f29619d5d30',227,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-10-28T01:59:45',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(2753,1900,366,'ENV_SUS_PLST','RES 17-483','ENV_SUS_PLST ENV_SUS_CLIM ENV_SUS_RECY The resolution in support of repealing state pesticide preemption is primarily concerned with environmental issues. Given the agenda item''s focus on pesticides, it aligns closely with environmental sustainability efforts, particularly those aimed at reducing harmful chemicals in the environment, paralleling the goals of plastic reduction and sustainability captured under ENV_SUS_PLST. This code encompasses initiatives focused on minimizing environmental harm, and while it specifically mentions plastic, the broader goal of curtailing environmental damage through chemical reductions is applicable. Additionally, pesticide discussions often intersect with climate and recycling policies, justifying the secondary suggestions.','S. RES 17-483 Resolution in Support of the Repeal of the State Pesticide Preemption','18801246-58e8-4b57-8359-3fcc59103dd4',227,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('S. RES 17-483 Resolution in Support of the Repeal of the State Pesticide Preemption\nVillage Manager Pavlicek stated that State Law has a Home Rule preemption. The\nVillage of Oak Park is a Home Rule unit of government, which means that the Village\nBoard can enact such things that are not expressly prohibited by State Law. The\npreemption means that the State of Illinois expressly prohibits local regulation of the use\nof pesticides. State Law does allow Chicago and Cook County to make those\nregulations. This resolution would be an effort to lobby the Sate and show that the Village\nBoard is supportive of a change in State Legislation that would allow Home Rule units of\ngovernment to enact local regulations regarding the use of pesticides.\nPeggy McGrath, representing Go Green Oak Park. Ms. McGrath thanked the Board for\nlooking at this topic and spoke about the negative effects of pesticides.\nDavid Holmquist, representing Go Green Oak Park. Mr. Holmquist concurred with Ms.\nMcGrath and noted that the determination of the new administration in Washington to\ndestroy environmental protections makes it even more important for local governments to\ntake control.\nVillage Trustees Tucker and Button Ott thanked Ms. McGrath and Mr. Holmquist for their\nwork and for educating them on this issue.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Brewer, seconded by Village Trustee Tucker,\nthat this Resolution be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the\nvote was as follows:\nAYES: 6 - Village Trustee Salzman, Village President Abu-Taleb, Village Trustee Button Ott,\nVillage Trustee Brewer, Village Trustee Barber, and Village Trustee Tucker\nNAYS: 0\nABSENT: 1 - Village Trustee Lueck\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
