INSERT INTO items VALUES(2971,2559,619,'ENV_SUS_PLST','ORD 17-239','ENV_SUS_PLST PROC_ORD_RULES ENV_SUS_RECY The first choice is **ENV_SUS_PLST** because the agenda item involves amending the village code to make a pilot program regarding single-use bags mandatory. This relates directly to environmental sustainability efforts focused on reducing the usage of single-use plastics, as outlined by the classification for plastic reduction. The ordinance indicates a move towards environmental responsibility and aligns with initiatives to reduce the environmental impact of such materials, making it a fitting classification under plastic reduction efforts.','Q. ORD 17-239 An Ordinance Amending Chapter 20 ("Public Health"), Article 14 ("Retail Single-Use Bag Pilot Program") of the Oak Park Village Code to Make the Village''s Single-Use Bag Program Mandatory','93166382-de58-4882-bbb9-555253133d7e',244,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('Q. ORD 17-239 An Ordinance Amending Chapter 20 (“Public Health”), Article 14 (“Retail\nSingle-Use Bag Pilot Program”) of the Oak Park Village Code to Make the\nVillage’s Single-Use Bag Program Mandatory\nVillage Manager Pavlicek stated that this amendment will make it mandatory for retailers\n5,000 sq. ft. or over to charge 10 cents for both paper and plastic bags effective January\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(2972,3178,140,'AFF_HOUS_DEV','RES 17-619','AFF_HOUS_DEV ZONE_USE_RES PUB_ENG_HEAR The first choice, AFF_HOUS_DEV, was made because the agenda item involves a Memorandum of Understanding related to a school addition project, which suggests a potential connection to development and construction. While this particular item specifically mentions a school addition rather than housing, the development aspect aligns best with AFF_HOUS_DEV given the structured nature of a large project that typically involves planning, approvals, and possibly joint agreements between municipal entities and other organizations. Additionally, school infrastructure projects often carry similarities with housing initiatives due to overlapping regulatory and developmental frameworks.','R. RES 17-619 A Resolution Approving a Memorandum of Understanding with the Board of Education of Oak Park Elementary School District No. 97 Related to the Proposed Holmes School Addition Project and Authorizing its Execution','a19b5e9b-a528-4da0-917e-546ac9b0563f',244,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('R. RES 17-619 A Resolution Approving a Memorandum of Understanding with the Board\nof Education of Oak Park Elementary School District No. 97 Related to the\nProposed Holmes School Addition Project and Authorizing its Execution\nVillage Manager Pavlicek stated that earlier this year, a right of entry agreement was\napproved to allow D97 to do soil testing on the proposed site. Since then, D97 has asked\nfor a Memorandum of Understanding outlining the transfer of vacated Village right-of way\nto D97 and relocation of utilities from the site to allow for construction of an addition to\nHolmes School. Should D97 decide to expand on to the west, an intergovernmental\nagreement will be brought to the Board.\nVillage Trustee Andrews thanked staff for making this happen, as it has been a complex\nissue. Village Trustee Boutet concurred.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Andrews, seconded by Village Trustee Tucker,\nthat this Resolution be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the\nvote was as follows:\nAYES: 7 - Village Trustee Button, Village Trustee Taglia, Village President Abu-Taleb, Village\nTrustee Tucker, Village Trustee Moroney, Village Trustee Boutet, and Village\nTrustee Andrews\nNAYS: 0\nABSENT: 0\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
