INSERT INTO items VALUES(3503,6586,868,'PUB_ENG_CITIZEN','MOT 19-103','``` PUB_ENG_CITIZEN RACE_EQ_COMM PUB_ENG_PROC ``` The agenda item concerns creating a small grant program focused on equity, diversity, and inclusion—key themes that suggest community engagement, citizen involvement, and municipal support for equity initiatives. I classified it under `PUB_ENG_CITIZEN` as my first choice because this category includes citizen oversight initiatives and efforts in community engagement, making it the closest fit for a program designed to involve and benefit the local community around those themes. Additionally, initiating such a grant program typically involves engaging citizens directly through outreach and participation in civic endeavors.','AF. MOT 19-103 A Motion to Direct Staff to Create Guidelines for an Equity, Diversity and Inclusion Small Grant Program for Adoption by the Village Board at a Subsequent Meeting','9e8637d4-3a54-4a9f-8e31-32852ac30471',291,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-10-28T01:59:45',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(3504,7454,483,'TRANS_INF_TRAFFIC','ORD 19-77','TRANS_INF_TRAFFIC PROC_ORD_RULES TRANS_INF_EXP The first choice, TRANS_INF_TRAFFIC, was made because the agenda item specifically involves setting and amending speed limits, which directly relates to traffic-related issues, such as road safety and traffic management. The establishment of speed limits is a classic traffic control measure, aligning with "Traffic-related issues, including new stop signs, traffic calming measures, and road safety" as described under the TRANS_INF_TRAFFIC symbolic name in the classification system.','AG. ORD 19-77 An Ordinance Establishing a Maximum Speed Limit of Twenty Five Miles Per Hour on Madison Street by Amending Section 15-1-10 ("Speed Limits") of the Oak Park Village Code','8800363d-a5f9-4850-a8eb-42198e4aa821',291,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-10-28T01:59:45',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(3505,7937,386,'PUB_WRK_ROADS','RES 19-261','PUB_WRK_ROADS PUB_WRK_UTIL OTHER The first choice, PUB_WRK_ROADS, was selected because the agenda item involves maintenance work on infrastructure related to sidewalks, which falls under the broader category of road and street maintenance activities. "Pressure washing and sealing of sidewalks" indicates maintenance efforts to improve and preserve the condition of public pathways, akin to road maintenance. While specific to sidewalks rather than streets, the nature of the work aligns more closely with road-related public works than utility projects or unrelated categories.','P. RES 19-261 A Resolution Approving an Independent Contractor Agreement with P.W.S. Environmental, Inc. for the Pressure Washing and Sealing of Bluestone Sidewalks in an Amount Not to Exceed $91,815.00 and Authorizing its Execution','9447a509-1b29-403d-ab27-935b4d014967',291,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('P. RES 19-261 A Resolution Approving an Independent Contractor Agreement with\nP.W.S. Environmental, Inc. for the Pressure Washing and Sealing of\nBluestone Sidewalks in an Amount Not to Exceed $91,815.00 and\nAuthorizing its Execution\nDirector of Public Works John Wielebnicki stated that this is for six different areas in the\nVillage. This is the second time staff bid this out, as the first bidders were significantly\nhigher.\nVillage Trustee Andrews stated that he pulled this from Consent in order to get statistics,\nwhich were given. He asked if concrete needs to be sealed on a regular basis as well.\nMr. Wielebnicki said it does not. He explained why bluestone needs to be sealed and\nthat the longer it is in place, the less often sealing is needed. Village Trustee Andrews\nwanted to point out that whenever the Village purchases bluestone, the high cost of\nmaintenance is ongoing as well as the initial cost being significantly higher than\nconcrete.\nVillage Trustee Taglia asked if bluestone lasts longer than concrete. Mr. Wielebnicki\nstated that if installed properly, it is.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Andrews, seconded by Village Trustee\nWalker-Peddakotla, that this Resolution be adopted. The motion was approved.\nThe roll call on the vote was as follows:\nAYES: 7 - Village President Abu-Taleb, Village Trustee Andrews, Village Trustee Boutet,\nVillage Trustee Buchanan, Village Trustee Moroney, Village Trustee Taglia, and\nVillage Trustee Walker-Peddakotla\nNAYS: 0\nABSENT: 0\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
