INSERT INTO items VALUES(3913,3138,590,'FIN_MGT_TAX','ORD 16-134','FIN_MGT_TAX FIN_MGT_BUDGET FIN_MGT_GRANTS The agenda item primarily revolves around the issuance of tax-exempt bonds and the associated levy and collection of taxes to repay these bonds, which directly aligns with fiscal management and tax-related functions within a municipality. Therefore, "FIN_MGT_TAX" is the best classification, as it deals specifically with tax levies and fiscal management to ensure funding—perfectly capturing the essence of the ordinance described.','AA. ORD 16-134 An Ordinance Providing for the Issuance of $10,395,000 Tax Exempt General Obligation Corporate Purpose Bonds, Series 2016E and Providing for the Levy and Collection of a Direct Annual Tax for the Payment of the Principal of and Interest on S','a3196fe3-3d04-4354-9970-4767ded733a5',325,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('AA. ORD 16-134 An Ordinance Providing for the Issuance of $10,395,000 Tax Exempt\nGeneral Obligation Corporate Purpose Bonds, Series 2016E and Providing\nfor the Levy and Collection of a Direct Annual Tax for the Payment of the\nPrincipal of and Interest on Said Bonds.\nVillage Manager Pavlicek stated that earlier today, Speer Financial completed a\ncompetitive sale of bonds in the amount of $10.395 million. This issuance is for the\nVillage''s final payment to the developer of the Lake and Forest project for the\npublic/private partnership that constructed the public parking garage component of the\ndevelopment.\nRaphaliata McKenzie of Speer Financial stated that the best bid received was from\nRobert W. Baird & Co. at a 3.71% interest rate and payments of $765,000 annually for 20\nyears. They were pleased with the interest rate considering the volatility of the market in\nrecent weeks. She noted that the Village has maintained their A1 rating from Moody''s\nand AA rating from Standard and Poor''s.\nKevin McCanna, also from Speer, stated that the Village''s extra funding towards pensions\nwill reflect favorably on them, as bond rating services are very focused on pensions. They\nhave seen many communites'' ratings go down, specifically due to underfunded pension\nliability.\nThere was a discussion regarding the previous lower bond rate and perhaps waiting for\nrates to come down. Mr. McCanna explained why rates are higher and that there is no\nguarantee that they will not increase.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Brewer, seconded by Village Trustee Tucker,\nthat this Ordinance be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the\nvote was as follows:\nAYES: 6 - Village Trustee Salzman, Village Trustee Abu-Taleb, Village Trustee Lueck, Village\nTrustee Brewer, Village Trustee Barber, and Village Trustee Tucker\nNAYS: 0\nABSENT: 1 - Village Trustee Button Ott\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(3914,3728,105,'ECON_DEV_REDEV','ORD 16-143','ECON_DEV_REDEV ZONE_USE_AMEND FIN_MGT_TAX The first choice, ECON_DEV_REDEV, was made because the agenda item directly involves a redevelopment project plan in a specific area of the village, which aligns well with the description of incentives and projects aimed at revitalizing commercial areas and supporting local business expansion. The mention of amending the redevelopment plan and the focus on a project area highlights the emphasis on economic development through redevelopment efforts.','AB. ORD 16-143 An Ordinance Supplementing and Amending the Redevelopment Plan and Redevelopment Project for the Harlem and Garfield Redevelopment Project Area of the Village of Oak Park by Providing for Receipt of the 23rd Year of Incremental Property Taxe','59d9f4ba-810f-475b-8d38-ead54bf97611',325,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('AB. ORD 16-143 An Ordinance Supplementing and Amending the Redevelopment Plan and\nRedevelopment Project for the Harlem and Garfield Redevelopment\nProject Area of the Village of Oak Park by Providing for Receipt of the 23rd\nYear of Incremental Property Taxes in the 24th Year\nVillage Manager Pavlicek stated that the Harlem Garfield TIF will end on December 31,\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
INSERT INTO items VALUES(3915,3833,544,'TRANS_INF_TRAFFIC','RES 16-337','TRANS_INF_TRAFFIC PUB_WRK_ROADS ZONE_USE_COMM The agenda item primarily deals with an amendment to a professional services agreement related to surveying services for the "Madison Street Streetscape Project," which implies enhancements or alterations for a specific street. This connects directly to transportation infrastructure, particularly the planning and execution of projects affecting traffic and road safety. Therefore, "TRANS_INF_TRAFFIC," which covers traffic-related issues including road safety and streetscape projects, is the most fitting classification.','M. RES 16-337 A Resolution Approving an Amendment to the Professional Services Agreement with V3 Companies of Illinois Ltd., for Surveying Services for the Madison Street Streetscape Project for an additional $11,000 and Authorizing its Execution','fa8ffd16-9392-4261-badd-5dfdb6d5a699',325,'2024-10-28T01:59:45','2024-11-05T04:38:59',replace('M. RES 16-337 A Resolution Approving an Amendment to the Professional Services\nAgreement with V3 Companies of Illinois Ltd., for Surveying Services for the\nMadison Street Streetscape Project for an additional $11,000 and\nAuthorizing its Execution\nVillage Manager Pavlicek noted that the Board had previously awarded a contract to V3\nfor surveying services for topographical information related to drainage and other elements\nfor the road diet project associated with the Madison Street TIF.\nChris Donovan. Mr. Donovan commented that there has been no public mention of the\nMadison Street road diet proposal since July. He asked when that discussion will take\nplace.\nDirector of Public Works John Wielebnicki stated that this additional survey is necessary\nto obtain any drainage issues, etc., related to the bend for the areas north and south of\nMadison.\nVillage President Abu-Taleb discussed why the Village needs to seize this opportunity to\ndevelop Madison Street. He noted that revenue from Village owned property will never\ncome unless they start development.\nIt was moved by Village Trustee Tucker, seconded by Village Trustee Salzman,\nthat this Resolution be adopted. The motion was approved. The roll call on the\nvote was as follows:\nAYES: 6 - Village Trustee Salzman, Village Trustee Abu-Taleb, Village Trustee Lueck, Village\nTrustee Brewer, Village Trustee Barber, and Village Trustee Tucker\nNAYS: 0\nABSENT: 1 - Village Trustee Button Ott\n','\n',char(10)),NULL);
